Nikkei 225 Gains for Sixth Day as Energy Shares Gain, Bridgestone Advances

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a
-- 
2011-02-21T07:58:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-21/nikkei-225-declines-for-first-time-in-six-days-as-mideast-unrest-spreads.html
Japanese stocks rose, sending the  Nikkei 225  Stock Average to its longest winning streak in more
than a year, as unrest in the Middle East boosted the price of
oil and Bridgestone Corp. jumped following a brokerage upgrade.  Inpex Corp., Japan’s biggest oil explorer, increased 1.7
percent. Bridgestone, the world’s largest tiremaker, jumped 5.8
percent after Goldman Sachs Group Inc. raised its rating to
“buy.” Softbank Corp., Japan’s third-largest mobile-phone
operator, climbed 5.6 percent on affiliate Renren.com’s plan for
a $500 million U.S. initial public offering this year.  “There is uncertainty in the Middle East, which may affect
oil production and transportation,” said  Yoshinori Nagano , a
senior strategist in Tokyo at Daiwa Asset Management Co., which
oversees about $104 billion.  The Nikkei 225 Stock Average gained 0.1 percent to
10,857.53 at the close in Tokyo, rising for a sixth consecutive
day, the longest winning streak since December 2009. The Nikkei
fell as much as 0.5 percent earlier. The broader Topix index
increased 0.1 percent to 974.63, with about as many shares up as
down. Both gauges rose to their highest levels since April 30.  The Topix has risen 8.4 percent so far this year, the most
among indexes for the world’s six-biggest equity markets.
The gain has raised the price of stocks to 16.5 times estimated
earnings on average, compared with 14 times on Standard & Poor’s
500 Index, and 11.5 times on the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.  Tiremakers, Softbank  Makers of tires and other rubber products gained the most
among the Topix’s 33 industry groups. Bridgestone jumped 5.8
percent to 1,760 yen, the biggest gain on the Nikkei. Sumitomo
Rubber Industries Ltd., Japan’s second-largest tiremaker,
increased 2.4 percent to 929 yen after Goldman Sachs boosted its
target price on the shares to 1,150 yen from 1,100 yen.  Softbank, the country’s exclusive dealer of Apple Inc.’s
iPhone, gave the Topix its biggest boost and was Japan’s most-
actively traded stock by value. The carrier climbed 5.6 percent
to 3,420 yen after a report that affiliate Renren.com,  China ’s
largest social-networking service, is preparing an initial
public offering.  Separately, Mizuho Securities Co. raised Softbank’s price
estimate to 4,230 yen from 2,920 yen, maintaining an
“outperform” rating.  Inpex gained 1.7 percent to 597,000 yen, while Japan
Petroleum Exploration Co., the nation’s second-largest oil
explorer, advanced 2.7 percent to 4,005 yen. Oil rose in New
York to as high as $91.70 a barrel as violence escalated in  Libya , heightening concern supplies will be disrupted as turmoil
spreads through the Middle East and North Africa.  Libyan Crackdown  Libyan security forces attacked anti-government protesters
in a crackdown that  Human Rights Watch  said has killed more than
200 people, and violence flared in Yemen, Djibouti and Bahrain.  In China, Japan’s biggest export destination, authorities
acted to halt an online call for a “Jasmine Revolution,”
dispatching police and rounding up more than a dozen lawyers and
activists, the  New York  Times reported.  Tokyo Electron Ltd., the world’s second-largest maker of
semiconductor equipment, declined 2.1 percent to 5,540 yen.
Shin-Etsu Chemical Co., a maker of silicon wafers, dropped 1.4
percent to 4,775 yen. The book-to-bill ratio, a measure of
industry health for manufacturers of chipmaking equipment, fell
to 0.99 in January, the lowest level since at least July,
according to figures from the Semiconductor Equipment
Association of Japan.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Norie Kuboyama in Tokyo at 
 nkuboyama@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
